e access with authorization2star  aIn the past, happiness studies has been dominated by the work of philosophers, economists and psychologists, but more recently there has been a growing interest from social scientist into the natures of happiness and wellbeing. This original collection draws on the latest empirical research to explore the practical challenges facing happiness researchers today, such as how to conduct happiness research in different cultural contexts, how to theorise wellbeing or how to operationalise definitions of happiness in qualitative and biographical research. By uniquely combining the critical approach of sociology with techniques from other disciplines, the contributors illuminate new approaches to the study of happiness and well-being.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Research.2bisacsh1 aBeel, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCieslik, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCieslik, Mark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCoulthard, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibbons, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolthus, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Kelly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManzenreiter, Wolfram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSuojanen, Ilona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThin, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTross, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 